solutions.content:
* dp[i][j] denotes the side length of the square with (i, j) in the lower right corner
	* Intuitivly the 0-th row and the 0-th column of dp are exactly the same as matrix
	    *  **dp(0, j) = matrix(0, j)  for each j**
		*  **dp(i, 0) = matrix(i, 0) for each i**
	* Recurrence formula is
		*  **dp(i, j) = 0 if matrix(i, j) == 0 else min(dp(i - 1, j - 1), dp(i - 1, j), dp(i, j - 1)) + 1**
	*  Time Complexity: O(MN)
	*  **Space Complextiy: O(MN) or O(N) or O(min(M,N)) or O(1)**
		*  Space Complextiy O(MN) is enough to AC, but if you are interested in space complexity optimization, you may continue to read.
		*  Note that dp(i, ) only depends on dp(i - 1, ), so we only need to record the results of two rows of dp at most and reduce the space comlexity to O(N).
		*  Furthermore we can rotate the matrix so that the number of columns is less than or equal to the number of rows, and then we reduce the space comlexity to O(min(M,N)).
		*  **In python we can use matrix itself as dp and modify in-place, so that the extra space complexity is O(1)**

* Note that base on the definition of dp, dp[-1][-1] is not always the maximum of dp
* In the picture, I only drew the case where the sides of the three squares are equal. If they are not equal, dp[i][j] will depend on the one with the smallest side of the three squares.

